---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { isBlogPublished } from '../../lib/blogGate';
import BlogCrossLinks from '../../components/BlogCrossLinks.astro';

const slug = Astro.url.pathname.replace('/blog/', '').replace(/\/$/, '');
const isPublished = await isBlogPublished(slug);
if (!isPublished) return Astro.redirect('/404');
---

<Layout title="How Many Liters in a Gallon? US vs Imperial" description="How many liters in a gallon? US vs Imperial gallons explained with examples for fuel, milk, and water conversion." keywords="gallons to liters, US gallon, imperial gallon, how many liters in a gallon, gallon conversion, fuel gallon, gallon to litres">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Volume</span>
      </nav>
      <BlogCrossLinks title="How Many Liters in a Gallon? US vs Imperial" />
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">June 29, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>The gallon is used for everything from fuel to milk to paint — but not all gallons are equal. The US gallon and the Imperial (UK) gallon are different sizes, which causes confusion when comparing prices, fuel economy, or recipes across countries.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">The Answer</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">1 US gallon = 3.785 liters</p>
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400 mt-1">1 Imperial gallon = 4.546 liters</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">The Imperial gallon is about 20% larger</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Why Two Different Gallons?</h2>
      <p>Both come from English measurement history but diverged in the early 1800s:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>The US adopted the Queen Anne wine gallon (231 cubic inches) when it became independent</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>Britain redefined the gallon in 1824 as the volume of 10 pounds of water (277.4 cubic inches)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>Result: the Imperial gallon is larger because it was based on weight of water rather than an arbitrary volume</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Gallon Breakdown</h2>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>1 US gallon = 4 US quarts = 8 US pints = 128 US fl oz = 3,785 mL</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>1 Imperial gallon = 4 Imperial quarts = 8 Imperial pints = 160 UK fl oz = 4,546 mL</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>1 US gallon = 0.833 Imperial gallons</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>1 Imperial gallon = 1.2 US gallons</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Practical Examples</h2>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Fuel:</strong> Gas at $3.50/US gallon = $0.92/liter. Petrol at £1.50/liter = £6.82/Imperial gallon = about $5.68/US gallon</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Swimming pool:</strong> A typical pool holds 15,000 US gallons = 56,781 liters</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Daily water intake:</strong> The recommended "8 glasses" is about half a US gallon = 1.9 liters</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Paint coverage:</strong> 1 US gallon of paint covers about 350-400 sq ft</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Who Uses Which?</h2>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>US gallon:</strong> United States, some Latin American countries (for fuel)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Imperial gallon:</strong> Was used in UK, Canada, Australia — now mostly replaced by liters</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Liters:</strong> The rest of the world (official metric unit)</span>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>Even the UK and Canada have largely abandoned the gallon. Fuel is sold by the liter in both countries now, though Canadians still occasionally reference gallons colloquially.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Quick Mental Math</h2>
      <p>For US gallons to liters, multiply by 4 and subtract a little (technically multiply by 3.785). For a quick estimate, think "just under 4 liters per gallon." A 20-gallon fuel tank holds about 76 liters.</p>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Try It Now</h3>
        <a href="/convert/volume" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 text-white text-sm font-semibold hover:bg-amber-600 transition-colors">Open Volume Converter →</a>
      </div>
    
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 p-4 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl">
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">🔗 Try our converter: <a href="/convert/volume" class="text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 font-bold hover:underline">Open Converter →</a></p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
